msDesc.head: Processus seu negocium canonizacionis B. Katerine de Vadstenis

p.note: thin cardboard, silk paper in layers.

binding.p: Modern binding. in light brown leather, with nine double strands of thread fastening the quires. On the the back flap a note with text in black ink in a modern hand: Processus Canonisationis Beatae Katarinae 1477. On the inside a note in pencil: Häftad 1987 i befintliga hål followed by a signature.

The original red velvet wrappers, with green silk on the , described by e.g. Collijn (1943)
and Odelberg (1965)
. The velvet is woven in a pomegranate pattern and embroidered with ornaments in gold and silver. On the edges a border in gold and silver thread, probably woven in Vadstena monastery. On the spine an embroidery with green and red silk threads, originally fastening the quires. Another manuscript, the so-called Libellus rubeus containing the legend and miracles of St Katarina, was originally kept within the wrappers, and is mentioned on (in quodam paruo libello Rubeo continente xxxvi folia); this manuscript is now in the Ossolineum library (Poland). The rectangular holes on the spine indicate that the seals were originally fastened here, as well as on the lower part of the front cover. Collijn (1943)
mentions remnants of green wax (no longer visible) on the front cover. Holes for the threads of the seals are visible near the spine. The wrappers were repaired in 1960.

history.provenance:
The volume was produced in Vadstena, Strängnäs and other places where witnesses were heard during the canonisation process. It was sent to Rome and may have been kept in the Birgitta house for some time. In the 17th century, the manuscript was kept at the Royal Castle in Cracow, see Collijn (1943)
. It was found at the Dominican convent Ad Sanctam Trinitatem in Cracow by Beda Dudík
in .
history.acquisition:
Purchased by G. E. Klemming
for the National Library in . The acquistion process is described in Collijn (1943)
and Odelberg (1965)
.

msItem.title: Report on the hearings of witnesses during Katarina's canonisation process, 1475-1477.
msItem.incipit: necnon meritis et miraculis dicte domine Katerine sancte memorie ac miraculorum eius crebrescencia et veritate admisimus
msItem.explicit: In quorum omnium et singulorum fidem et euidens Testimonium premissorum Sigilla nostra vnacum supscripcionibus notariorum seu scribarum nostrorum supra et infrascriptorum presentibus actis nostri apponi iussimus impendenda

msItem.title: Notarial acts
msItem.incipit: Et ego Conradus gregorii Clericus lincopensis diocesis publicus imperiali auctoritate notarius
msItem.explicit: Ideo hoc presens Registrum seu hec presencia acta manu alterius scripta et registrata de communi voluntate et requisicione prefatorum Dominorum Commissariorum subscripsi Signoque et nomine meis solitis et consuetis vnacum Dictorum Dominorum Commissariorum Sigillorum appensione signaui In fidem et testimonium omnium et singulorum premissorum Rogatus et requisitus

supportDesc.foliation: Contemporary foliation in brown ink xi-clxii ().
supportDesc.condition: First quire, consisting of ten leaves, missing. Four holes visible on all quires, through which the ribbons for the seals were originally drawn. Red mould-stains throughout the volume, particularly large on . On , the ink has been damaged by damp, but the text is still legible.

layout.note: Guidelines in lead (not visible on all pages).

handDesc.handNote:
Hybrida (chancery) with occasional looped ascenders. The scribe is Conradus Gregorii, priest in the diocese of Linköping, see Kolsrud (1935)
and Collijn (1943)
. On a mention of Conradus as a scribe: hoc presens instrumentum publicum instrumentum manu mea fideliter scriptum.
Hybrida with occasional looped ascenders. The scribe is Ingemundus Petri, priest in the diocese of Linköping.
Hybrida. The scribe is Olaus Johannis, priest in the diocese of Strängnäs.
Gothic cursive. The scribe is Olaus Andreae, priest in the diocese of Strängnäs.

p.note: Top of page in pencil by a modern hand: A 93, in the outer margin: 1475.

Marginal annotations in light brown ink by a late medieval hand throughout the volume. According to Kolsrud (1935)
, the scribe of these marginal notes is Johannes Huseman, a notary in Rome ca .

decoDesc.decoNote: Penwork initials in brown ink over 2-12 lines. Some initials are extended along the margin, for example on .
